    <<speech "jaylie">>Where did you grow up?<</speech>>

    Allura shifts on the bed, stretching one leg out beneath the silk and draping her arm across a cushion.

    <<speech "allura">>Far from here. Farther than you'd guess, I think.<</speech>>

    Her tone is gentle, not evasive—like she's choosing each word with care rather than caution.

    <<speech "allura">>A small village in the eastern cliffs of Taramel. You wouldn't find it on most maps. A place of rock and wind and stubborn people who didn't take kindly to anything they couldn't explain. Especially not a girl with gold eyes, blue skin, and a tail.<</speech>>

    She doesn't sound bitter, but there's a weight behind the words—something old and settled.

    <<speech "allura">>My mother was from that village, but one day when I was around 8 years old I went out to watch the other kids play Fae-Ball. When I went back to our hut my mother was gone along with just about everything we owned, which wasn't much to begin with.<</speech>>

    She watches your face closely as she talks. When you don't seem to be offering comment she continues.

    <<speech "allura">>I stayed there only as long as I had to after that. I truly had no one and spent most of my time begging or scrounging for food. Eventually, I gathered enough coin to make it to the next closest town, down out of the mountains. Then I did that again and then again, until I eventually found myself across an ocean and living in Bastion.<</speech>>

    <<speech "jaylie">>Do you miss it? The cliffs. The people.<</speech>>

    <<speech "allura">>Not even for a second, but sometimes when I close my eyes and dream, I can still feel the moutain air blowing on my back, as if I'm not to forget.<</speech>>

